<section id=3D"S1" class=3D"ltx_section">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section">1 </span>Introduction</h2>

<div id=3D"S1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Transformer-based <cite class=3D"ltx_cite=
 ltx_citemacro_cite">Vaswani<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</=
span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib1" title=3D"Atte=
ntion is all you need" class=3D"ltx_ref">2017</a>]</cite> language models o=
f code have achieved state-of-the-art performance across a wide range of so=
ftware analytics tasks, including clone detection <cite class=3D"ltx_cite l=
tx_citemacro_cite">Arshad<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</spa=
n> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib175" title=3D"Codeb=
ert for code clone detection: a replication study" class=3D"ltx_ref">2022</=
a>]</cite>, code summarization <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">=
Ahmed<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https=
://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib376" title=3D"Automatic semantic augmen=
tation of language model prompts (for code summarization)" class=3D"ltx_ref=
">2024</a>]</cite>, vulnerability prediction <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_ci=
temacro_cite">Ding<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a =
href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib127" title=3D"Vulnerabilit=
y detection with code language models: how far are we?" class=3D"ltx_ref">2=
024</a>]</cite>, and code search <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite=
">Chen<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"http=
s://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib128" title=3D"Code search is all you n=
eed? improving code suggestions with code search" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024</a=
>]</cite>. However, despite their impressive capabilities, the adoption of =
these models remains limited, particularly in consumer-grade devices (e.g.,=
 laptops) and latency-sensitive applications, due to their substantial comp=
utational demands, slow inference speed, and considerable energy consumptio=
n and carbon footprint <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Shi<span=
 class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.o=
rg/html/2511.05476#bib.bib6" title=3D"Compressing pre-trained models of cod=
e into 3 mb" class=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>], Schwartz<span class=3D"ltx_text l=
tx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#b=
ib.bib62" title=3D"Green ai" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>]</cite>. For instan=
ce, CodeBERT, a widely used code language model with 125 million parameters=
 and a size of 476 MB, can incur up to 1.5 seconds of latency, consume 0.32=
 kWh of energy, and emit 0.14 kg of CO<sub id=3D"S1.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_su=
b">2</sub> on consumer-grade laptops.<span id=3D"footnote1" class=3D"ltx_no=
te ltx_role_footnote"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">1</sup><span class=3D"lt=
x_note_outer"><span class=3D"ltx_note_content"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark"=
>1</sup><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note">1</span>When integrated into I=
DEs, CodeBERT may be invoked thousands of times daily by a developer, refle=
cting typical usage patterns <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">He=
llendoorn<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"h=
ttps://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib96" title=3D"When code completion f=
ails: a case study on real-world completions" class=3D"ltx_ref">2019</a>]</=
cite>.</span></span></span> To address these practical challenges, the soft=
ware engineering research community has recently begun exploring knowledge =
distillation methods <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Hinton<spa=
n class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.=
org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib41" title=3D"Distilling the knowledge in a neura=
l network" class=3D"ltx_ref">2015</a>]</cite> to develop extremely compact =
models that reduce model size, lower inference latency, and mitigate enviro=
nmental impact while maintaining task performance <cite class=3D"ltx_cite l=
tx_citemacro_cite">Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> =
[<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib6" title=3D"Compressin=
g pre-trained models of code into 3 mb" class=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib8" title=3D"Greening large lan=
guage models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024a</a>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv=
.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib10" title=3D"Efficient and green large language=
 models for software engineering: vision and the road ahead" class=3D"ltx_r=
ef">2024b</a>], Wei<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a=
 href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib16" title=3D"Towards gree=
ner yet powerful code generation via quantization: an empirical study" clas=
s=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>], Saad<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.<=
/span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib18" title=3D"AL=
PINE: an adaptive language-agnostic pruning method for language models for =
code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024</a>], d=E2=80=99Aloisio<span class=3D"ltx_text=
 ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476=
#bib.bib20" title=3D"On the compression of language models for code: an emp=
irical study on codebert" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024</a>], Chen<span class=3D"l=
tx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/251=
1.05476#bib.bib114" title=3D"Smaller but better: self-paced knowledge disti=
llation for lightweight yet effective lcms" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>]</ci=
te>.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S1.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Knowledge distillation (KD) transfers kno=
wledge from a large teacher model to a smaller student<span id=3D"footnote2=
" class=3D"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">2</sup>=
<span class=3D"ltx_note_outer"><span class=3D"ltx_note_content"><sup class=
=3D"ltx_note_mark">2</sup><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note">2</span>In t=
his study, the term student model refers to the compressed model obtained t=
hrough knowledge distillation, while the term teacher model denotes the ori=
ginal uncompressed model.</span></span></span> model, maintaining comparabl=
e accuracy while requiring significantly fewer computational resources. In =
this context, Shi et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Shi<sp=
an class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv=
.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib8" title=3D"Greening large language models of c=
ode" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024a</a>]</cite> introduced <span id=3D"S1.p2.1.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span>, a genetic algorithm-b=
ased approach that compresses code-specialized language models (e.g., CodeB=
ERT <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Feng<span class=3D"ltx_text=
 ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476=
#bib.bib138" title=3D"Codebert: a pre-trained model for programming and nat=
ural languages" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>]</cite>) from 476 MB and 125 mil=
lion parameters to only 3 MB with minimal loss in accuracy. Although KD eff=
ectively reduces computational costs and environmental impact, student mode=
l performance is typically evaluated using traditional accuracy-based metri=
cs that assess whether the student model=E2=80=99s task performance on grou=
nd-truth labels remains comparable to that of the teacher model. However, t=
his form of evaluation offers only a surface-level view and may overlook cr=
itical discrepancies in <span id=3D"S1.p2.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_b=
old">behavioral fidelity</span>=E2=80=94<span id=3D"S1.p2.1.3" class=3D"ltx=
_text ltx_font_italic">the extent to which a student model deeply mimics th=
e predictive behavior and internal representations of its teacher counterpa=
rt</span>.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S1.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.p3.1" class=3D"ltx_p">To investigate this limitation, we evalua=
te the student model=E2=80=99s ability to mimic the teacher by performing s=
imple yet effective adversarial attacks <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemac=
ro_cite">Yang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib177" title=3D"Natural attack f=
or pre-trained models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2022</a>], Zhang<span clas=
s=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/ht=
ml/2511.05476#bib.bib176" title=3D"Generating adversarial examples for hold=
ing robustness of source code processing models" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020a</a=
>], Zeng<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"ht=
tps://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib379" title=3D"An extensive study on =
pre-trained models for program understanding and generation" class=3D"ltx_r=
ef">2022</a>], Tian<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a=
 href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib15" title=3D"Code differe=
nce guided adversarial example generation for deep code models" class=3D"lt=
x_ref">2023</a>]</cite>. These attacks involve renaming identifiers and app=
lying semantic-preserving code transformations informed by the contextual s=
emantics of each code snippet. The empirical results reveal that although t=
he student models achieve performance comparable to the teacher before adve=
rsarial perturbations, their performance degrades substantially under adver=
sarial attacks, with up to <span id=3D"S1.p3.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_fon=
t_bold">285%</span> greater performance loss than the teacher model. This f=
inding indicates that the student model does not deeply mimic the teacher=
=E2=80=99s predictive behavior and internal representations, highlighting t=
he limitations of the traditional accuracy-based evaluation, which often ov=
erlooks more profound behavioral discrepancies between teacher and student =
models.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S1.p4" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.p4.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Despite these observations, current evalu=
ation practices for knowledge distillation predominantly rely on accuracy-b=
ased metrics, which provide only a superficial assessment of model performa=
nce <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text =
ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#=
bib.bib6" title=3D"Compressing pre-trained models of code into 3 mb" class=
=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib=
8" title=3D"Greening large language models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024a=
</a>], Panichella [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib29" =
title=3D"Metamorphic-based many-objective distillation of llms for code-rel=
ated tasks" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>]</cite>. As demonstrated in the empi=
rical analysis, these metrics do not capture whether the student model main=
tains the teacher=E2=80=99s predictive behavior and internal representation=
s, especially under adversarial attacks. As a result, to the best of our kn=
owledge, there is no systematic framework for evaluating the behavioral fid=
elity of student models beyond task-level correctness. This limitation unde=
rscores the need for a nuanced evaluation framework that goes beyond accura=
cy to assess how deeply a student model mimics the predictive behavior and =
internal representations of its teacher, providing a more comprehensive und=
erstanding of model alignment under knowledge distillation.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S1.p5" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.p5.1" class=3D"ltx_p">To fill this gap, we introduce <span id=
=3D"S1.p5.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span>, a te=
sting framework inspired by metamorphic testing principles in software engi=
neering <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Chen<span class=3D"ltx_=
text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.0=
5476#bib.bib103" title=3D"Metamorphic testing: a review of challenges and o=
pportunities" class=3D"ltx_ref">2018</a>]</cite>, to evaluate the behaviora=
l fidelity of the student model in knowledge distillation. In contrast to t=
raditional accuracy-based evaluation, which compares model performance agai=
nst ground-truth labels, <span id=3D"S1.p5.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_=
italic">MetaCompress</span> performs a head-to-head comparison of student a=
nd teacher model outputs across a set of behavior-preserving metamorphic re=
lations, enabling a more nuanced assessment of behavioral fidelity. We desi=
gn four metamorphic relations, grounded in strong empirical evidence from m=
anual investigations, that capture discrepancies in the behavioral fidelity=
 of student models, ranging from prediction-level disagreement to divergenc=
es in the probability distribution.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S1.p6" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.p6.1" class=3D"ltx_p">We empirically evaluate <span id=3D"S1.p6=
.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> on two widely =
studied software engineering tasks, <span id=3D"S1.p6.1.2" class=3D"ltx_tex=
t ltx_font_italic">clone detection</span> and <span id=3D"S1.p6.1.3" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">vulnerability prediction</span>, using two po=
pular language models of code, <span id=3D"S1.p6.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx=
_font_italic">CodeBERT</span> <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">F=
eng<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https:/=
/arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib138" title=3D"Codebert: a pre-trained mod=
el for programming and natural languages" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>]</cite=
> and <span id=3D"S1.p6.1.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">GraphCodeBE=
RT</span> <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Guo<span class=3D"ltx=
_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.=
05476#bib.bib140" title=3D"Graphcodebert: pre-training code representations=
 with data flow" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>]</cite>. To distill their small=
er student models, we apply three state-of-the-art knowledge distillation t=
echniques designed for language models of code: <span id=3D"S1.p6.1.6" clas=
s=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span> <cite class=3D"ltx_cite lt=
x_citemacro_cite">Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [=
<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib6" title=3D"Compressing=
 pre-trained models of code into 3 mb" class=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>]</cite>, =
<span id=3D"S1.p6.1.7" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span> <ci=
te class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib=
_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib=
8" title=3D"Greening large language models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024a=
</a>]</cite>, and <span id=3D"S1.p6.1.8" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic"=
>MORPH</span> <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Panichella [<a hr=
ef=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib29" title=3D"Metamorphic-bas=
ed many-objective distillation of llms for code-related tasks" class=3D"ltx=
_ref">2025</a>]</cite>. Our extensive experiments show that <span id=3D"S1.=
p6.1.9" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> can reveal b=
ehavioral fidelity discrepancies of up to <span id=3D"S1.p6.1.10" class=3D"=
ltx_text ltx_font_bold">62%</span> across four metamorphic relations that t=
raditional accuracy-based metrics fail to detect. Furthermore, the ablation=
 study shows that <span id=3D"S1.p6.1.11" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic=
">MetaCompress</span> remains robust and effectively identifies behavioral =
fidelity divergence, even when both teacher and student models are evaluate=
d on transformed inputs.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S1.p7" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.p7.1" class=3D"ltx_p">In summary, the main contributions of thi=
s paper are as follows:</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S1.p8" class=3D"ltx_para">
<ul id=3D"S1.I1" class=3D"ltx_itemize">
<li id=3D"S1.I1.i1" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">=E2=80=A2</span>=20
<div id=3D"S1.I1.i1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.I1.i1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S1.I1.i1.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Insight:</span> We are the first to demonstrate=
 that traditional accuracy-based metrics fall short in capturing behavioral=
 fidelity between student and teacher models by measuring adversarial robus=
tness. To address this, we reframe this evaluation challenge as a classical=
 software testing problem and address it through the lens of metamorphic te=
sting. Ensuring behavioral fidelity is critical because it guarantees that =
the student model not only provides correct outputs but also behaves consis=
tently across scenarios, just like the teacher model, which is essential fo=
r complex tasks like coding.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S1.I1.i2" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">=E2=80=A2</span>=20
<div id=3D"S1.I1.i2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.I1.i2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S1.I1.i2.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Technique:</span> We propose <span id=3D"S1.I1.=
i2.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span>, a novel =
output-based metamorphic testing framework grounded in four behavior-preser=
ving metamorphic relations to systematically evaluate the behavioral fideli=
ty of student models for code</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S1.I1.i3" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">=E2=80=A2</span>=20
<div id=3D"S1.I1.i3.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S1.I1.i3.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S1.I1.i3.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Evaluation:</span> We conduct a comprehensive e=
valuation of <span id=3D"S1.I1.i3.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic=
">MetaCompress</span>, demonstrating its effectiveness in uncovering discre=
pancies in the behavioral fidelity of student models for code that are ofte=
n overlooked by traditional accuracy-based metrics.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S1.I1.i4" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
