ding" class=3D"ltx_ref">2018</a>]</cite>.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S2.SS1.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.SS1.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Language models for code can be broad=
ly classified into three categories: (1) encoder-only, (2) decoder-only, an=
d (3) encoder-decoder models <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Ze=
ng<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://=
arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib379" title=3D"An extensive study on pre-tr=
ained models for program understanding and generation" class=3D"ltx_ref">20=
22</a>]</cite>. Encoder-only models (e.g., CodeBERT <cite class=3D"ltx_cite=
 ltx_citemacro_cite">Feng<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</spa=
n> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib138" title=3D"Codeb=
ert: a pre-trained model for programming and natural languages" class=3D"lt=
x_ref">2020</a>]</cite> and GraphCodeBERT <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citem=
acro_cite">Guo<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib140" title=3D"Graphcodebert: p=
re-training code representations with data flow" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>=
]</cite>) process the entire input simultaneously and are primarily used fo=
r discriminative tasks, such as classification (e.g., vulnerability predict=
ion and clone detection). Decoder-only models (e.g., CodeGPT <cite class=3D=
"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Lu<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et a=
l.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib378" title=
=3D"Codexglue: a machine learning benchmark dataset for code understanding =
and generation" class=3D"ltx_ref">2021</a>]</cite>, StarCoder <cite class=
=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Lozhkov<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_eta=
