<section id=3D"S2.SS2" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">2.2 </span>Model Compression</h3=
>

<div id=3D"S2.SS2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">A significant barrier to the real-wor=
ld deployment of language models of code is their substantial computational=
 overhead, high memory demands, and environmental impact (e.g., carbon emis=
sions) <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Schwartz<span class=3D"l=
tx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/251=
1.05476#bib.bib62" title=3D"Green ai" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>], Xu and M=
cAuley [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib54" title=3D"A =
survey on model compression and acceleration for pretrained language models=
" class=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>]</cite>. To mitigate these challenges and adva=
nce sustainability, a widely adopted strategy known as <span id=3D"S2.SS2.p=
1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">model compression</span> offers a=
 solution that reduces the resource consumption of such models without sign=
ificantly compromising performance. Model compression refers to the process=
 of reducing a large, computationally intensive model into a smaller, more =
efficient version suitable for deployment on resource-constrained devices (=
e.g., consumer-grade laptops). In addition to deployment benefits, model co=
mpression improves inference speed and enhances overall resource efficiency=
. Algorithmically, the fundamental model compression techniques include: <s=
pan id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">pruning</span> =
<cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Sanh<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx=
_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib=
.bib40" title=3D"Movement pruning: adaptive sparsity by fine-tuning" class=
=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>]</cite>, <span id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text=
 ltx_font_italic">quantization</span> <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro=
_cite">Zafrir<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib39" title=3D"Q8bert: quantized=
 8bit bert" class=3D"ltx_ref">2019</a>]</cite>, <span id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.1.4" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">knowledge distillation</span> <cite clas=
s=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Hinton<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_eta=
l"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib41" =
title=3D"Distilling the knowledge in a neural network" class=3D"ltx_ref">20=
15</a>]</cite>, <span id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.1.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_itali=
c">neural architecture search</span> <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_=
cite">Elsken<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib112" title=3D"Neural architect=
ure search: a survey" class=3D"ltx_ref">2019</a>]</cite>, <span id=3D"S2.SS=
2.p1.1.6" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">weight sharing &amp; hashing</=
span> <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Chen<span class=3D"ltx_te=
xt ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.054=
76#bib.bib111" title=3D"Compressing neural networks with the hashing trick"=
 class=3D"ltx_ref">2015</a>]</cite>, and <span id=3D"S2.SS2.p1.1.7" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">low-rank factorization</span> <cite class=3D"=
ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Sainath<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> =
et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib99" titl=
e=3D"Low-rank matrix factorization for deep neural network training with hi=
gh-dimensional output targets" class=3D"ltx_ref">2013</a>]</cite>-each meth=
od uniquely contributes to model optimization. Among these, pruning, quanti=
zation, and knowledge distillation (KD) have emerged as the most prominent =
and widely adopted approaches for compressing language models of code in re=
cent software engineering research. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_c=
ite">Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"ht=
tps://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib6" title=3D"Compressing pre-trained =
models of code into 3 mb" class=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>, <a href=3D"https://ar=
xiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib8" title=3D"Greening large language models o=
f code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024a</a>], Wei<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_et=
al"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib16"=
 title=3D"Towards greener yet powerful code generation via quantization: an=
 empirical study" class=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>], d=E2=80=99Aloisio<span class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/htm=
l/2511.05476#bib.bib20" title=3D"On the compression of language models for =
code: an empirical study on codebert" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024</a>], Chen<spa=
n class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.=
org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib114" title=3D"Smaller but better: self-paced kno=
wledge distillation for lightweight yet effective lcms" class=3D"ltx_ref">2=
025</a>], Liu<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib31" title=3D"PIONEER: improvin=
g the robustness of student models when compressing pre-trained models of c=
ode" class=3D"ltx_ref">2026</a>], Afrin<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal=
"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib32" t=
itle=3D"Is quantization a deal-breaker? empirical insights from large code =
models" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>]</cite>.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S2.SS2.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.SS2.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">While pruning and quantization primar=
ily remove redundant parameters or reduce numerical precision to achieve co=
mpactness, their ability to produce highly compact models is inherently lim=
ited, as aggressive compression often results in substantial degradation of=
 representational capacity. In contrast, KD offers a distinct advantage by =
enabling the creation of a smaller student model that can closely approxima=
te, and in some cases replicate, the predictive behavior of its larger teac=
her counterpart. Through this process, the student learns to mimic the teac=
her=E2=80=99s functional behavior using soft targets such as probability di=
stributions, internal embeddings, or logits generated by the teacher. This =
allows the student model to preserve the teacher=E2=80=99s predictive behav=
ior and generalization while maintaining a significantly reduced computatio=
nal footprint. In the context of language models of code, KD has emerged as=
 a promising compression technique for producing a deployable model that re=
tains functional equivalence with its teacher, although the extent to which=
 a student model truly mimics its teacher=E2=80=99s behavior remains largel=
y unexplored in software engineering.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S2.SS3" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">2.3 </span>Metamorphic Testing</=
h3>

<div id=3D"S2.SS3.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.SS3.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Metamorphic testing (MT) is a propert=
y-based testing paradigm widely adopted for validating software systems in =
the absence of a test oracle or when one is difficult to define, a challeng=
e commonly referred to as the oracle problem <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_ci=
temacro_cite">Chen<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a =
href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib103" title=3D"Metamorphic =
testing: a review of challenges and opportunities" class=3D"ltx_ref">2018</=
a>], Zhang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"=
https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib104" title=3D"Search-based inferen=
ce of polynomial metamorphic relations" class=3D"ltx_ref">2014</a>]</cite>.=
 Rather than verifying the correctness of individual outputs in isolation, =
MT addresses this issue by evaluating whether the program under test exhibi=
ts expected relationships between outputs across a set of well-defined meta=
morphic relations (MRs). An MR specifies a necessary property that captures=
 the expected relationship between multiple inputs and their corresponding =
outputs. These relations are derived from the problem domain=E2=80=99s inhe=
rent semantics and define how the output should change (or remain consisten=
t) when the input is systematically modified. This paradigm is beneficial f=
or testing complex systems such as machine learning models, scientific comp=
uting software, or simulation tools, where correctness is difficult to asse=
rt for individual outputs but consistency across related cases can be meani=
ngfully assessed <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Yang<span clas=
s=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/ht=
ml/2511.05476#bib.bib105" title=3D"Hallucination detection in large languag=
e models with metamorphic relations" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025a</a>], Xie<span=
 class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.o=
rg/html/2511.05476#bib.bib106" title=3D"Testing and validating machine lear=
ning classifiers by metamorphic testing" class=3D"ltx_ref">2011</a>], Chen<=
span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arx=
iv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib107" title=3D"Metamorphic testing: a new appr=
oach for generating next test cases" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>], Xiao<span=
 class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.o=
rg/html/2511.05476#bib.bib108" title=3D"Metamorphic testing of deep learnin=
g compilers" class=3D"ltx_ref">2022</a>], Segura<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx=
_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib=
.bib109" title=3D"Metamorphic testing of restful web apis" class=3D"ltx_ref=
">2018</a>]</cite>.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S2.SS3.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.SS3.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">In this study, we adapt MT to evaluat=
e how deeply a student model produced via KD mimics its teacher model=E2=80=
=99s behavior. Unlike conventional MT, we do not apply transformations to t=
he input samples. Instead, we define MRs between the teacher and student mo=
dels=E2=80=99 outputs, ensuring that when both receive the same input, thei=
r outputs exhibit a consistent relationship. These teacher=E2=80=93student =
MRs capture multiple aspects of behavioral fidelity, including agreement in=
 predicted labels, similarity in probability distributions, and calibration=
 consistency. By systematically evaluating these MRs, we gain a deeper unde=
rstanding of behavioral fidelity between the teacher and student models bey=
ond accuracy-based evaluation.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S2.SS4" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">2.4 </span>Adversarial Attack</h=
3>

<div id=3D"S2.SS4.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.SS4.p1.5" class=3D"ltx_p">An adversarial attack refers to the d=
eliberate process of crafting adversarial examples by introducing subtle pe=
rturbations to the original inputs. Although these perturbed instances appe=
ar almost identical to their original counterparts from a human perspective=
, they can cause the model to yield erroneous or inconsistent outputs. The =
concept of adversarial attack was first introduced by Zegedy et al.&nbsp;<c=
ite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Szegedy<span class=3D"ltx_text lt=
x_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bi=
b.bib287" title=3D"Intriguing properties of neural networks" class=3D"ltx_r=
ef">2013</a>]</cite>, who demonstrated that state-of-the-art image classifi=
ers can be misled by carefully designed pixel-level modifications that rema=
in imperceptible to human observers. Formally, given a classifier <math id=
=3D"S2.SS4.p1.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"f:X\rightarrow Y" display=
=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo lspace=3D"0.=
278em" rspace=3D"0.278em">:</mo><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=
=86=92</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-te=
x">f:X\rightarrow Y</annotation></semantics></math> that correctly predicts=
 the label <math id=3D"S2.SS4.p1.2.m2" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"y_{tru=
th}\in Y" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi=
>y</mi><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>=
r</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>u</mi><mo lspace=
=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>t</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=
=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=E2=88=88</mo><mi>Y</mi>=
</mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">y_{truth}\in Y</annotatio=
n></semantics></math> for an input <math id=3D"S2.SS4.p1.3.m3" class=3D"ltx=
_Math" alttext=3D"x\in X" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics=
><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=E2=88=88</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D=
"application/x-tex">x\in X</annotation></semantics></math>, an adversarial =
attack generates a perturbed version <math id=3D"S2.SS4.p1.4.m4" class=3D"l=
tx_Math" alttext=3D"x^{\prime}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><sem=
antics><msup><mi>x</mi><mo>=E2=80=B2</mo></msup><annotation encoding=3D"app=
lication/x-tex">x^{\prime}</annotation></semantics></math> such that <math =
id=3D"S2.SS4.p1.5.m5" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"f(x^{\prime})\neq f(x)=
=3Dy_{truth}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mrow=
><mi>f</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mrow><mo stretc=
hy=3D"false">(</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mo>=E2=80=B2</mo></msup><mo stretchy=3D=
"false">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=E2=89=A0</mo><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo lspace=3D=
"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo><mi>x=
</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=3D</mo><msub><mi>y</mi=
><mrow><mi>t</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>r</mi>=
<mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>u</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em=
" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>t</mi><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=
=E2=80=8B</mo><mi>h</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"applic=
ation/x-tex">f(x^{\prime})\neq f(x)=3Dy_{truth}</annotation></semantics></m=
ath>.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S2.SS4.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.SS4.p2.2" class=3D"ltx_p">In continuous domains such as images,=
 producing visually indistinguishable adversarial examples is relatively st=
raightforward. However, generating adversarial examples for discrete domain=
s like source code is considerably more complex due to the rigid syntactic =
and grammatical structure of programming languages&nbsp;<cite class=3D"ltx_=
cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Zhang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.=
</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib61" title=3D"T=
owards robustness of deep program processing models=E2=80=94detection, esti=
mation, and enhancement" class=3D"ltx_ref">2022</a>, <a href=3D"https://arx=
iv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib176" title=3D"Generating adversarial examples=
 for holding robustness of source code processing models" class=3D"ltx_ref"=
>2020a</a>]</cite>. As a result, adversarial examples designed to attack la=
nguage models of code must meet three fundamental requirements. <span id=3D=
"S2.SS4.p2.2.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">First</span>, the perturba=
tion must effectively mislead the model and reduce its predictive performan=
ce. <span id=3D"S2.SS4.p2.2.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Second</spa=
n>, the perturbed code must remain syntactically correct, adhering to the f=
ormal rules of the programming language; for example, in Python, identifier=
s cannot begin with digits and may only contain letters, digits, or undersc=
ores. <span id=3D"S2.SS4.p2.2.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Third</sp=
an>, the perturbed code <math id=3D"S2.SS4.p2.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" altt=
ext=3D"x^{\prime}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><msup>=
<mi>x</mi><mo>=E2=80=B2</mo></msup><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-te=
x">x^{\prime}</annotation></semantics></math> must preserve the semantics o=
f the original code <math id=3D"S2.SS4.p2.2.m2" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=
=3D"x" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>x</mi><annotat=
ion encoding=3D"application/x-tex">x</annotation></semantics></math>, maint=
aining identical functionality and behavior when executed under the same co=
nditions. When an input instance is modified in accordance with these const=
raints to generate a perturbed version, the resulting instance constitutes =
an adversarial example; if it causes the model to produce an incorrect or i=
nconsistent output, it is regarded as an adversarial attack.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S2.SS5" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">2.5 </span>Adversarial Robustnes=
s</h3>

<div id=3D"S2.SS5.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S2.SS5.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Adversarial robustness describes a mo=
del=E2=80=99s capacity to maintain its predictive performance and stability=
 when exposed to adversarial perturbations. A model is considered adversari=
ally robust if it continues to generate consistent, accurate outputs despit=
e deliberate input modifications intended to mislead it. In the context of =
machine learning, this concept reflects a model=E2=80=99s resilience to adv=
ersarial attacks that exploit its sensitivity to small perturbations in the=
 input space <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Szegedy<span class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/htm=
l/2511.05476#bib.bib287" title=3D"Intriguing properties of neural networks"=
 class=3D"ltx_ref">2013</a>], Zhang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> e=
