<section id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2" class=3D"ltx_subsubsection">
<h4 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsubsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsubsection">3.1.2 </span>Datasets and Sub=
jects</h4>

<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">To minimize experimental bias in=
 evaluating whether the student model deeply mimics the teacher=E2=80=99s p=
redictive behavior and internal representations during knowledge distillati=
on, we adopt the same models and datasets used in the knowledge distillatio=
n=E2=80=93based approaches described in Section <a href=3D"https://arxiv.or=
g/html/2511.05476#S3.SS1.SSS1" title=3D"3.1.1 Knowledge Distillation Approa=
ches =E2=80=A3 3.1 Study Design =E2=80=A3 3 Empirical Study =E2=80=A3 A Met=
amorphic Testing Perspective on Knowledge Distillation for Language Models =
of Code: Does the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><spa=
n class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">3.1.1</span></a>. Specifically, we select =
CodeBERT <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Feng<span class=3D"ltx=
_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.=
05476#bib.bib138" title=3D"Codebert: a pre-trained model for programming an=
d natural languages" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>]</cite> and GraphCodeBERT <=
cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Guo<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_b=
ib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.b=
ib140" title=3D"Graphcodebert: pre-training code representations with data =
flow" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>]</cite> models and two well-studied downst=
ream tasks: clone detection and vulnerability prediction, which serve as st=
andard benchmarks in knowledge distillation research for software engineeri=
ng <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text l=
tx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#b=
ib.bib6" title=3D"Compressing pre-trained models of code into 3 mb" class=
=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib=
8" title=3D"Greening large language models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024a=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib10" title=3D"Effi=
cient and green large language models for software engineering: vision and =
the road ahead" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024b</a>], Panichella [<a href=3D"https:=
//arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib29" title=3D"Metamorphic-based many-obje=
ctive distillation of llms for code-related tasks" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</=
a>], Liu<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"ht=
tps://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib31" title=3D"PIONEER: improving the =
robustness of student models when compressing pre-trained models of code" c=
lass=3D"ltx_ref">2026</a>]</cite>.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p2.1.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Clone Detection (CD):</span> This task aim=
s to determine whether two given code snippets are syntactically or semanti=
cally equivalent. To streamline the fine-tuning process, we adopt the filte=
red BigCloneBench dataset <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Svajl=
enko<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https:=
//arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib74" title=3D"Towards a big data curated =
benchmark of inter-project code clones" class=3D"ltx_ref">2014</a>]</cite> =
provided by Wang et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Wang<sp=
an class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv=
.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib75" title=3D"Detecting code clones with graph n=
eural network and flow-augmented abstract syntax tree" class=3D"ltx_ref">20=
20a</a>]</cite>. The final dataset includes 90,102 training examples, along=
 with 4,000 examples each for validation and testing.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p3.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p3.1.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Vulnerability Prediction (VP):</span> This=
 task aims to determine whether a given code snippet contains a vulnerabili=
ty. We conduct our experiments using the Devign<span id=3D"footnote5" class=
=3D"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">5</sup><span c=
lass=3D"ltx_note_outer"><span class=3D"ltx_note_content"><sup class=3D"ltx_=
note_mark">5</sup><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note">5</span><a href=3D"h=
ttps://sites.google.com/view/devign" title=3D"" class=3D"ltx_ref ltx_url lt=
x_font_typewriter">https://sites.google.com/view/devign</a></span></span></=
span> dataset, introduced by Zhou et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citema=
cro_cite">Zhou<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib146" title=3D"Devign: effectiv=
e vulnerability identification by learning comprehensive program semantics =
via graph neural networks" class=3D"ltx_ref">2019</a>]</cite>. The dataset =
comprises 27,318 functions sourced from two widely used open-source C libra=
ries, FFmpeg and Qemu. Each function is manually annotated to indicate whet=
her it contains vulnerabilities. We use the CodeXGLUE benchmark splits <cit=
e class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Lu<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_e=
tal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib37=
8" title=3D"Codexglue: a machine learning benchmark dataset for code unders=
tanding and generation" class=3D"ltx_ref">2021</a>]</cite>, including train=
ing, development, and test sets with 27,318, 2,732, and 2,732 examples, res=
pectively.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p4" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p4.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p4.1.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">CodeBERT</span> is a pre-trained language =
model that shares the same architecture and a similar pre-training strategy=
 as RoBERTa <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Liu [<a href=3D"htt=
ps://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib133" title=3D"Roberta: a robustly opt=
imized bert pretraining approach" class=3D"ltx_ref">2019</a>]</cite>. It co=
nsists of twelve Transformer layers, each with 12-headed multi-head attenti=
on mechanisms and a hidden size of 768. CodeBERT is pre-trained using two o=
bjectives: <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p4.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_itali=
c">masked language modeling</span>, which predicts masked tokens, and <span=
 id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p4.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">replaced toke=
n detection</span>, which identifies substituted tokens in the input. The m=
odel is trained on bimodal data comprising natural language=E2=80=93code pa=
irs across six programming languages from the CodeSearchNet dataset <cite c=
lass=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Husain<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_=
etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib1=
47" title=3D"Codesearchnet challenge: evaluating the state of semantic code=
 search" class=3D"ltx_ref">2019</a>]</cite>.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p5" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p5.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS2.p5.1.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">GraphCodeBERT</span> shares CodeBERT=E2=80=
=99s architecture but incorporates data-flow information from source code d=
uring pre-training. Additionally, it introduces a pre-training task that pr=
edicts whether a data flow edge exists between two nodes.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS3" class=3D"ltx_subsubsection">
<h4 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsubsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsubsection">3.1.3 </span>Adversarial Atta=
ck Approaches</h4>

<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS3.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS3.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">In this study, adversarial attac=
ks are employed to evaluate how deeply the student model mimics the teacher=
=E2=80=99s predictive behavior and internal representations during knowledg=
e distillation. Adversarial attacks are typically categorized as black-box =
or white-box, depending on the attacker=E2=80=99s level of access to the mo=
del. Following the recommendation of Du et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_=
citemacro_cite">Du<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a =
href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib145" title=3D"An extensive=
 study on adversarial attack against pre-trained models of code" class=3D"l=
tx_ref">2023</a>]</cite>, we adopt black-box attacks, as they rely solely o=
n model outputs and are widely used for evaluating language models of code =
<cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Yang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx=
_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib=
.bib177" title=3D"Natural attack for pre-trained models of code" class=3D"l=
tx_ref">2022</a>], Zhang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span=
> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib176" title=3D"Genera=
ting adversarial examples for holding robustness of source code processing =
models" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020a</a>]</cite>. The perturbations introduced t=
hrough these attacks are deliberately subtle to maintain the syntactic and =
semantic integrity of the source code, as discussed in Section <a href=3D"h=
ttps://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S2.SS4" title=3D"2.4 Adversarial Attack =
=E2=80=A3 2 Preliminaries =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Testing Perspective on Kn=
owledge Distillation for Language Models of Code: Does the Student Deeply M=
imic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">2=
.4</span></a>, while inducing mispredictions. To this end, we employ three =
established black-box techniques: ALERT <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemac=
ro_cite">Yang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib177" title=3D"Natural attack f=
or pre-trained models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2022</a>]</cite>, Metropol=
is Hastings Modifier (MHM) <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Zhan=
g<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://a=
rxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib176" title=3D"Generating adversarial exampl=
es for holding robustness of source code processing models" class=3D"ltx_re=
f">2020a</a>]</cite>, and WIR-Random <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_=
cite">Zeng<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"=
https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib379" title=3D"An extensive study o=
n pre-trained models for program understanding and generation" class=3D"ltx=
_ref">2022</a>]</cite>, each of which performs identifier substitution to a=
ssess model robustness without altering code functionality. To further enha=
nce robustness evaluation, we also employ <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS3.p1.1.1" c=
lass=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">CODA</span> <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_cit=
emacro_cite">Tian<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a h=
ref=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib15" title=3D"Code differenc=
e guided adversarial example generation for deep code models" class=3D"ltx_=
ref">2023</a>]</cite>, a black-box attack technique that combines identifie=
r renaming with semantic-preserving code transformations. This enables asse=
ssment of model robustness under a wider range of functionally equivalent p=
rogram variations.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS3.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS3.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS3.p2.1.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">ALERT</span> considers both operational an=
d natural semantics, using greedy and genetic algorithms to select substitu=
tions, with 30 candidates per identifier. <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS3.p2.1.2" c=
lass=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">MHM</span> utilizes Metropolis-Hastings sam=
pling for iterative identifier substitution, with a maximum of 100 iteratio=
ns and 30 candidates per iteration. <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS3.p2.1.3" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">WIR-Random</span> ranks identifiers based on th=
eir impact on model predictions and replaces them sequentially with randoml=
y chosen candidates. In contrast to these identifier-centric techniques, <s=
pan id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS3.p2.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">CODA</span> =
utilizes code differences between a target input and reference inputs with =
divergent predictions to guide adversarial example generation. It combines =
identifier renaming with semantic-preserving structural transformations. By=
 considering both the identifier level and structural differences, CODA gen=
erates functionally equivalent yet more diverse adversarial examples.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS3.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS3.p3.1" class=3D"ltx_p">It is important to note that onl=
y instances correctly classified before perturbation are included, ensuring=
 that the robustness evaluation is based exclusively on valid predictions a=
nd that any observed degradation in model performance is caused solely by a=
dversarial perturbations rather than pre-existing misclassifications <cite =
class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Yang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_e=
tal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib17=
7" title=3D"Natural attack for pre-trained models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref=
">2022</a>], Zhang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a =
href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib176" title=3D"Generating a=
dversarial examples for holding robustness of source code processing models=
" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020a</a>]</cite>.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS4" class=3D"ltx_subsubsection">
<h4 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsubsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsubsection">3.1.4 </span>Experimental Set=
tings</h4>

<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS4.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS4.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">We fine-tune CodeBERT using the =
hyperparameter settings and training pipeline provided by the CodeXGLUE ben=
chmark <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Lu<span class=3D"ltx_tex=
t ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.0547=
6#bib.bib378" title=3D"Codexglue: a machine learning benchmark dataset for =
code understanding and generation" class=3D"ltx_ref">2021</a>]</cite>, whil=
e for GraphCodeBERT, we adopt the settings specified in its original paper =
<cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Guo<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_=
bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.=
bib140" title=3D"Graphcodebert: pre-training code representations with data=
 flow" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>]</cite>. To ensure consistency across our=
 experiments, we adopt the data-splitting strategy used in knowledge distil=
lation=E2=80=93based approaches such as <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS4.p1.1.1" cla=
ss=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span> and <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS4.p1=
.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span>, which divide the tr=
aining data into two equal halves: one for fine-tuning and the other for kn=
owledge distillation. We apply the same fine-tuning split to all models. De=
spite being trained on only half of the original dataset, all models achiev=
e performance comparable to the state-of-the-art results reported in the Co=
deXGLUE benchmark <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Lu<span class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/htm=
l/2511.05476#bib.bib378" title=3D"Codexglue: a machine learning benchmark d=
ataset for code understanding and generation" class=3D"ltx_ref">2021</a>]</=
cite>, the GraphCodeBERT paper <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">=
Guo<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https:/=
/arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib140" title=3D"Graphcodebert: pre-training=
 code representations with data flow" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>]</cite>, a=
nd knowledge distillation=E2=80=93based compression studies such as <span i=
d=3D"S3.SS1.SSS4.p1.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</spa=
n>, <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS4.p1.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVAT=
AR</span>, and <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS4.p1.1.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_i=
talic">MORPH</span>.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5" class=3D"ltx_subsubsection">
<h4 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsubsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsubsection">3.1.5 </span>Evaluation Metri=
cs</h4>

<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Following the evaluation protoco=
ls of CodeXGLUE <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Lu<span class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/htm=
l/2511.05476#bib.bib378" title=3D"Codexglue: a machine learning benchmark d=
ataset for code understanding and generation" class=3D"ltx_ref">2021</a>]</=
cite>, Yang et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Yang<span cl=
ass=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/=
html/2511.05476#bib.bib177" title=3D"Natural attack for pre-trained models =
of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2022</a>]</cite>, and Shi et al. <cite class=3D"=
ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Shi<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et a=
l.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib6" title=3D"=
Compressing pre-trained models of code into 3 mb" class=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a=
>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib8" title=3D"Greening=
 large language models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024a</a>]</cite>, we use=
 <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">accuracy<=
/span> as the primary metric to evaluate model performance on downstream ta=
sks.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">To evaluate the performance of b=
oth teacher and student models under adversarial conditions, we measure the=
 effectiveness of the applied attack methods. A higher attack effectiveness=
 indicates greater model vulnerability to adversarial perturbations. We emp=
loy the <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p2.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">=
Attack Success Rate</span> (ASR) metric <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemac=
ro_cite">Yang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib177" title=3D"Natural attack f=
or pre-trained models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2022</a>]</cite> to measur=
e the effectiveness of an attack method. ASR measures the proportion of adv=
ersarial samples for which the model fails to produce a correct prediction =
after the attack and is formally defined as follows:</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<table id=3D"S3.E3" class=3D"ltx_equation ltx_eqn_table">

<tbody><tr class=3D"ltx_equation ltx_eqn_row ltx_align_baseline">
<td class=3D"ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_left_padleft"></td>
<td class=3D"ltx_eqn_cell ltx_align_left"><math id=3D"S3.E3.m1" class=3D"lt=
x_Math" alttext=3D"\text{ASR}=3D\frac{|\{x\in X\wedge M(x^{\prime})\neq M(x=
)\}|}{\left|\left\{x\in X\mid M(x)=3Dy\right\}\right|}" display=3D"block" i=
ntent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mtext>ASR</mtext><mo>=3D</mo><mfrac><m=
row><mo stretchy=3D"false">|</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=3D"false">{</mo><mrow><=
mi>x</mi><mo>=E2=88=88</mo><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>=E2=88=A7</mo><mrow><mi>M</m=
i><mo lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=3D"fal=
se">(</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mo>=E2=80=B2</mo></msup><mo stretchy=3D"false">)=
</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><mo>=E2=89=A0</mo><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo lspace=3D"0=
em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo><mi>x</=
mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow><mo stretchy=3D"false"=
>}</mo></mrow><mo stretchy=3D"false">|</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>|</mo><mrow><mo=
>{</mo><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=E2=88=88</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><mo fence=3D"true=
" lspace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=88=A3</mo><mrow><mrow><mi>M</mi><mo lsp=
ace=3D"0em" rspace=3D"0em">=E2=80=8B</mo><mrow><mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo=
><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=3D</mo><mi>y</mi=
></mrow><mo>}</mo></mrow><mo>|</mo></mrow></mfrac></mrow><annotation encodi=
ng=3D"application/x-tex">\text{ASR}=3D\frac{|\{x\in X\wedge M(x^{\prime})\n=
