</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p4" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p4.2" class=3D"ltx_p">Where <math id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p4=
.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"x" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":liter=
al"><semantics><mi>x</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">x</anno=
tation></semantics></math> is an original input, <math id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p4=
.2.m2" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"x^{\prime}" display=3D"inline" intent=
=3D":literal"><semantics><msup><mi>x</mi><mo>=E2=80=B2</mo></msup><annotati=
on encoding=3D"application/x-tex">x^{\prime}</annotation></semantics></math=
> is a modified input. A higher ASR value indicates greater attack effectiv=
eness, reflecting the models=E2=80=99 adversarial vulnerabilities.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p5" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p5.1" class=3D"ltx_p">The robustness of compressed mod=
els to adversarial attacks depends strongly on the quality of the adversari=
al examples generated. If these examples contain syntactic or semantic erro=
rs, model mispredictions may not accurately reflect a lack of robustness bu=
t rather the model=E2=80=99s inability to handle unrealistic inputs. Moreov=
er, excessive modifications to the original code during adversarial example=
 generation can lead to out-of-distribution instances, thereby reducing the=
 reliability of robustness assessments. To ensure a fair and meaningful eva=
luation, we conduct a qualitative analysis to assess the effectiveness of t=
he generated adversarial examples and to verify that the applied perturbati=
ons are minimal yet sufficient to mislead the models. Because the inputs fo=
r the selected software analytics tasks are source code, we employ four est=
ablished metrics from Du et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite"=
>Du<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https:/=
/arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib145" title=3D"An extensive study on adver=
sarial attack against pre-trained models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a=
>]</cite>: <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p5.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_itali=
c">Identifier Change Rate</span> (ICR), <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p5.1.2" cla=
ss=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Token Change Rate</span> (TCR), <span id=3D=
"S3.SS1.SSS5.p5.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Average Edit Distan=
ce</span> (AED), and <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p5.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_=
font_italic">Average Code Similarity</span> (ACS), to measure the quality o=
f the adversarial examples.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p6" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p6.4" class=3D"ltx_p">For a set of <math id=3D"S3.SS1.=
SSS5.p6.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"m" display=3D"inline" intent=3D=
":literal"><semantics><mi>m</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">=
m</annotation></semantics></math> adversarial examples, each <math id=3D"S3=
.SS1.SSS5.p6.2.m2" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"i" display=3D"inline" inte=
nt=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>i</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-=
tex">i</annotation></semantics></math>-th code snippet contains <math id=3D=
"S3.SS1.SSS5.p6.3.m3" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"k_{i}" display=3D"inlin=
e" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><msub><mi>k</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><annotat=
ion encoding=3D"application/x-tex">k_{i}</annotation></semantics></math> id=
entifiers, among which <math id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p6.4.m4" class=3D"ltx_Math" =
alttext=3D"n_{i}" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><msub><=
mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">n_{i}<=
/annotation></semantics></math> are modified to generate the adversarial ex=
ample. The <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p6.4.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold"=
>ICR</span> is computed as follows:</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p7" class=3D"ltx_para">
<table id=3D"S3.E4" class=3D"ltx_equation ltx_eqn_table">

<tbody><tr class=3D"ltx_equation ltx_eqn_row ltx_align_baseline">
<td class=3D"ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_left_padleft"></td>
<td class=3D"ltx_eqn_cell ltx_align_left"><math id=3D"S3.E4.m1" class=3D"lt=
x_Math" alttext=3D"\text{ICR}=3D\frac{\sum_{1}^{m}n_{i}}{\sum_{1}^{m}k_{i}}=
" display=3D"block" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mtext>ICR</mtext>=
<mo>=3D</mo><mfrac><mrow><msubsup><mo>=E2=88=91</mo><mn>1</mn><mi>m</mi></m=
subsup><msub><mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><msubsup><mo>=E2=88=91=
</mo><mn>1</mn><mi>m</mi></msubsup><msub><mi>k</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow>=
</mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\text{ICR}=3D\fra=
c{\sum_{1}^{m}n_{i}}{\sum_{1}^{m}k_{i}}</annotation></semantics></math></td=
>
<td class=3D"ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_left_padright"></td>
<td rowspan=3D"1" class=3D"ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_eqno ltx_align_middle ltx_a=
lign_right"><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_equation ltx_align_right">(4)</s=
pan></td>
</tr></tbody>
</table>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p8" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p8.1" class=3D"ltx_p">The <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p8.1=
.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">TCR</span> represents the proportion o=
f modified tokens relative to the total number of tokens in the original co=
de. The <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p8.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">AE=
D</span> quantifies the average number of character-level edits required to=
 transform one token into another, reflecting the textual intensity of the =
perturbation. The <span id=3D"S3.SS1.SSS5.p8.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_fon=
t_bold">ACS</span> measures cosine similarity between embeddings produced b=
y CodeBERT before and after the adversarial modifications. In general, high=
-quality adversarial examples are characterized by lower ICR, TCR, and AED =
values, along with higher ACS scores, indicating that the perturbations are=
 subtle yet effective while preserving code correctness.</p>
</div>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"S3.SS2" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">3.2 </span>Empirical Results</h3=
>

<div id=3D"S3.SS2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">This section presents the empirical r=
esults of our study designed to address the first research question, <span =
id=3D"S3.SS2.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">RQ1</span>: <span id=
=3D"S3.SS2.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Does the student mode=
l deeply mimic the teacher=E2=80=99s predictive behavior and internal repre=
sentations during knowledge distillation?</span></p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">We address this research question by =
evaluating the performance of student models under adversarial attacks rela=
tive to their teacher counterparts. In addition, we examine whether traditi=
onal accuracy-based evaluation can capture discrepancies in behavioral fide=
lity arising from the student models=E2=80=99 inability to deeply mimic the=
ir teacher models. Since <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p2.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_f=
ont_italic">AVATAR</span> outperforms <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p2.1.2" class=3D"l=
tx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span> and <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p2.1.3" c=
lass=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span> considers metamorphic robust=
ness during knowledge distillation, we compare the adversarial robustness o=
f student models compressed by <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p2.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text=
 ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span> and <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p2.1.5" class=3D"ltx=
_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span> with that of the teacher model for this=
 empirical analysis.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.p3.1" class=3D"ltx_p">To answer this research question, we =
first compare the performance of the teacher and student models on the orig=
inal, unperturbed test samples using <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p3.1.1" class=3D"lt=
x_text ltx_font_italic">accuracy</span> as the evaluation metric. Table <a =
href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S3.T1" title=3D"Table 1 =E2=80=A3=
 3.2 Empirical Results =E2=80=A3 3 Empirical Study =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic =
Testing Perspective on Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code: =
Does the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">1</span></a> presents the accuracy comparison bet=
ween teacher and student models across the clone detection and vulnerabilit=
y prediction tasks. Overall, the results indicate that the student models m=
aintain performance levels comparable to their teacher counterparts, with a=
ccuracy differences remaining within a narrow margin (mostly below 3%). For=
 instance, in clone detection, the student models CodeBERT and GraphCodeBER=
T compressed by <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p3.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_itali=
c">AVATAR</span> and <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p3.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_=
italic">MORPH</span> achieve accuracies close to those of their teacher mod=
els, with only minor reductions observed for <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p3.1.4" cla=
ss=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span>. A similar trend is observed =
in vulnerability prediction, where student models exhibit minimal degradati=
on and, in some cases, nearly identical performance to the teachers.</p>
</div>
