<div id=3D"S3.SS2.p4" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.p4.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Although the student models achieve t=
ask performance comparable to that of their teachers, these results provide=
 only a surface-level view of knowledge transfer. Accuracy-based evaluation=
 captures output correctness but may overlook discrepancies in behavioral f=
idelity between teacher and student models. Two models may achieve similar =
accuracy yet differ in representation, generalization, or response to pertu=
rbations. Hence, accuracy alone may not reveal whether the student model de=
eply mimics the teacher=E2=80=99s predictive behavior and internal represen=
tations. To address this, we further examine both models under adversarial =
attack scenarios to gain deeper insight into their behavioral fidelity.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.p5" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.p5.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Before analyzing model robustness und=
er adversarial conditions, we first evaluate the quality of the adversarial=
 examples generated by each attack technique. Excessive or unrealistic modi=
fications can distort the syntactic or semantic structure of the original c=
ode, leading to misleading robustness assessments. To ensure reliability, w=
e examine the syntactic and semantic integrity of the adversarial examples =
produced by each attack technique, confirming that the applied perturbation=
s are minimal yet effective. This analysis uses the CodeBERT and GraphCodeB=
ERT models trained on the clone detection task, with complete results for t=
he vulnerability prediction task available in our replication package. Sinc=
e all attack techniques modify only <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p5.1.1" class=3D"ltx=
_text ltx_font_italic">identifiers</span>, the resulting code retains its o=
riginal semantics. Figure <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S3.F=
1" title=3D"Figure 1 =E2=80=A3 3.2 Empirical Results =E2=80=A3 3 Empirical =
Study =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Testing Perspective on Knowledge Distillation=
 for Language Models of Code: Does the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" c=
lass=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">1</span></a> illustra=
tes the quality assessment of adversarial examples generated by different a=
ttack techniques against both teacher and student models.</p>
</div>
<figure id=3D"S3.F1" class=3D"ltx_figure"><img src=3D"https://arxiv.org/htm=
l/2511.05476v5/x1.png" id=3D"S3.F1.g1" class=3D"ltx_graphics ltx_centering =
ltx_img_square" width=3D"640" height=3D"737" alt=3D"Refer to caption">
<figcaption class=3D"ltx_caption ltx_centering"><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_=
tag_figure">Figure 1: </span>Quality analysis of adversarial examples acros=
s various models and evaluation metrics.</figcaption>
</figure>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.p6" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.p6.7" class=3D"ltx_p">Overall, the results indicate that th=
ese attack techniques effectively preserve the syntactic integrity of the g=
enerated adversarial examples. Specifically, the examples consistently exhi=
bit high ACS values and low TCR scores across both CodeBERT and GraphCodeBE=
RT models, demonstrating minimal syntactical distortion. The adversarial ex=
amples also maintain strong overall quality across the AED and ICR metrics =
for both the teacher and student models. Although a slight degradation is o=
bserved in certain cases=E2=80=94for instance, the MHM attack shows compara=
tively higher AED values=E2=80=94the overall differences remain limited. We=
 further perform the Friedman test <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_ci=
te">Friedman [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib97" title=
=3D"The use of ranks to avoid the assumption of normality implicit in the a=
nalysis of variance" class=3D"ltx_ref">1937</a>]</cite> to determine whethe=
r the three attack techniques (ALERT, MHM, and WIR-Random) generate adversa=
rial examples of significantly different quality for each model variant of =
CodeBERT and GraphCodeBERT. A <math id=3D"S3.SS2.p6.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math=
" alttext=3D"p" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>p</mi=
><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">p</annotation></semantics></mat=
h>-value below 0.05 indicates that the differences in the quality of advers=
arial examples produced by the three attack techniques are statistically si=
gnificant. However, the experimental results show no statistically signific=
ant differences among the attack methods for either CodeBERT (<math id=3D"S=
3.SS2.p6.2.m2" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"p=3D0.47" display=3D"inline" i=
ntent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>=3D</mo><mn>0.47</mn></mr=
ow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">p=3D0.47</annotation></semant=
ics></math>, <math id=3D"S3.SS2.p6.3.m3" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"p=3D=
0.37" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo=
>=3D</mo><mn>0.37</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">p=
=3D0.37</annotation></semantics></math>, and <math id=3D"S3.SS2.p6.4.m4" cl=
ass=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"p=3D0.37" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal=
"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>=3D</mo><mn>0.37</mn></mrow><annotation en=
coding=3D"application/x-tex">p=3D0.37</annotation></semantics></math> for T=
eacher, <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p6.7.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATA=
R</span>, and <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p6.7.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic"=
>MORPH</span>, respectively) or GraphCodeBERT (<math id=3D"S3.SS2.p6.5.m5" =
class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"p=3D0.63" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":liter=
al"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>=3D</mo><mn>0.63</mn></mrow><annotation =
encoding=3D"application/x-tex">p=3D0.63</annotation></semantics></math>, <m=
ath id=3D"S3.SS2.p6.6.m6" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"p=3D0.37" display=
=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>=3D</mo><mn>=
0.37</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">p=3D0.37</annota=
tion></semantics></math>, and <math id=3D"S3.SS2.p6.7.m7" class=3D"ltx_Math=
" alttext=3D"p=3D0.37" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><m=
row><mi>p</mi><mo>=3D</mo><mn>0.37</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"appli=
cation/x-tex">p=3D0.37</annotation></semantics></math> for Teacher, <span i=
d=3D"S3.SS2.p6.7.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span>, and <=
span id=3D"S3.SS2.p6.7.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span>, =
respectively). These results indicate that all three attack techniques gene=
rate adversarial examples of comparable quality across the evaluated metric=
s (ICR, TCR, AED, and ACS).</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.p7" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.p7.2" class=3D"ltx_p">Although the preceding results show t=
hat the adversarial examples essentially preserve syntactic and semantic qu=
ality across both teacher and student models, it remains important to exami=
ne whether any subtle quality differences exist between these two model cat=
egories. To investigate this, we compare the quality of adversarial example=
s generated by each attack technique for the teacher and student models acr=
oss all the evaluation metrics. The Wilcoxon signed-rank test <cite class=
=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Woolson [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html=
/2511.05476#bib.bib118" title=3D"Wilcoxon signed-rank test" class=3D"ltx_re=
f">2007</a>]</cite> is used to assess the statistical significance of these=
 differences. The comparison between the Teacher and <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p7.=
2.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span> models (<math id=3D"S=
3.SS2.p7.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"p=3D0.13" display=3D"inline" i=
ntent=3D":literal"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>=3D</mo><mn>0.13</mn></mr=
ow><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">p=3D0.13</annotation></semant=
ics></math>) and between the Teacher and <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p7.2.2" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span> models (<math id=3D"S3.SS2.p7.2.=
m2" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"p=3D0.85" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":l=
iteral"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>=3D</mo><mn>0.85</mn></mrow><annotat=
ion encoding=3D"application/x-tex">p=3D0.85</annotation></semantics></math>=
) indicates that the quality of adversarial examples remains statistically =
comparable, with no significant differences observed in either case. These =
findings suggest that the attack techniques generate adversarial examples o=
f similar syntactic and semantic integrity across both teacher and student =
models, confirming that the subsequent robustness analysis is based on adve=
rsarial inputs of consistent quality and that any observed performance degr=
adation can be attributed to the models=E2=80=99 inability to maintain robu=
stness against adversarial perturbations.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.p8" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.p8.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Having rigorously evaluated the quali=
ty of the generated adversarial examples, we next examine how effectively t=
he teacher and student models withstand adversarial attacks. Figure <a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S3.F2" title=3D"Figure 2 =E2=80=A3 3.=
2 Empirical Results =E2=80=A3 3 Empirical Study =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Tes=
ting Perspective on Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code: Doe=
s the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"l=
tx_text ltx_ref_tag">2</span></a> presents the Attack Success Rate (ASR) va=
lues for the teacher and student models (<span id=3D"S3.SS2.p8.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span> and <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p8.1.2" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span>) across the ALERT, MHM, and=
 WIR-Random attack techniques for both the clone detection and vulnerabilit=
y prediction tasks. Overall, the results indicate that student models produ=
ced through knowledge distillation exhibit substantially lower robustness t=
han their corresponding teacher models, as evidenced by consistently higher=
 ASR values across most attack settings, with only two exceptions. In the c=
lone detection task, the teacher model demonstrates lower robustness than t=
he <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p8.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</spa=
n> student model under the MHM and WIR-Random attacks, and than the <span i=
d=3D"S3.SS2.p8.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span> studen=
t model under the MHM attack. Although the robustness differences between t=
he teacher and student models are relatively small for the GraphCodeBERT mo=
del and the vulnerability prediction task, they are considerably larger in =
all other experimental settings. For instance, in the clone detection task =
with the CodeBERT model under the ALERT attack, the <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p8.1=
.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span> student model experien=
ces approximately three times greater performance degradation than the teac=
her model.</p>
</div>
<figure id=3D"S3.F2" class=3D"ltx_figure"><img src=3D"https://arxiv.org/htm=
l/2511.05476v5/x2.png" id=3D"S3.F2.g1" class=3D"ltx_graphics ltx_centering =
ltx_img_landscape" width=3D"660" height=3D"398" alt=3D"Refer to caption">
<figcaption class=3D"ltx_caption ltx_centering"><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_=
tag_figure">Figure 2: </span>Attack success rate (ASR) metric values across=
 identifier-renaming adversarial attack techniques, models, tasks, and know=
ledge distillation methods.</figcaption>
</figure>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.p9" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.p9.1" class=3D"ltx_p">To further assess the robustness of t=
eacher and student models to a broader class of semantic-preserving adversa=
rial perturbations, we conduct additional experiments using the CODA attack=
. Figure <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S3.F3" title=3D"Figur=
e 3 =E2=80=A3 3.2 Empirical Results =E2=80=A3 3 Empirical Study =E2=80=A3 A=
 Metamorphic Testing Perspective on Knowledge Distillation for Language Mod=
els of Code: Does the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref">=
<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">3</span></a> presents the Attack Succe=
ss Rate values under CODA. The results align with the trends observed for A=
LERT, MHM, and WIR-Random attacks. Across both tasks and model architecture=
s, student models trained via knowledge distillation generally achieve high=
er ASR values than their teacher counterparts, indicating reduced robustnes=
s to CODA-induced perturbations. This finding applies to both AVATAR and MO=
RPH students, confirming that the previously observed robustness degradatio=
n is not restricted to identifier-level attacks.</p>
</div>
<figure id=3D"S3.F3" class=3D"ltx_figure"><img src=3D"https://arxiv.org/htm=
l/2511.05476v5/x3.png" id=3D"S3.F3.g1" class=3D"ltx_graphics ltx_centering =
ltx_img_landscape" width=3D"660" height=3D"267" alt=3D"Refer to caption">
<figcaption class=3D"ltx_caption ltx_centering"><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_=
tag_figure">Figure 3: </span>Attack success rate (ASR) metric values across=
 CODA adversarial attack, models, tasks, and knowledge distillation methods=
.</figcaption>
</figure>
<div id=3D"S3.SS2.p10" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S3.SS2.p10.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Taken together, these findings sugge=
st that student models distilled from their teachers, particularly those pr=
oduced by <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p10.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AV=
ATAR</span> and, to a lesser extent, by <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p10.1.2" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span>, are more susceptible to adversa=
rial attacks than their teacher counterparts. Surprisingly, although <span =
id=3D"S3.SS2.p10.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span> gener=
ates student models by incorporating metamorphic robustness during knowledg=
e distillation, the resulting student models exhibit lower robustness than =
those produced by <span id=3D"S3.SS2.p10.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_it=
alic">AVATAR</span> across all the attack techniques for the GraphCodeBERT =
model in the vulnerability prediction task. The results further reveal that=
 student models fail to deeply mimic the teacher=E2=80=99s predictive behav=
ior and internal representations. Although knowledge distillation preserves=
 task accuracy under clean inputs, it weakens the model=E2=80=99s ability t=
o generate stable and consistent predictions when exposed to adversarial pe=
rturbations. As a result, traditional accuracy-based evaluation cannot capt=
ure these discrepancies in behavioral fidelity, which become evident only u=
nder adversarial conditions. These observations highlight the need for more=
 comprehensive evaluation frameworks that assess behavioral fidelity beyond=
 accuracy.</p>
</div>
