<section id=3D"S4.SS2.SSS1.Px2" class=3D"ltx_paragraph">
<h5 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_font_bold ltx_title_paragraph">Rationale</h5>

<div id=3D"S4.SS2.SSS1.Px2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS2.SSS1.Px2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">This MR captures the most in=
tuitive form of behavioral fidelity: <span id=3D"S4.SS2.SSS1.Px2.p1.1.1" cl=
ass=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">top-1</span> label consistency. Our empiri=
cal observations (as shown in Figure 3(b)) suggest that prediction disagree=
ment may be associated with divergence in model reasoning. Therefore, <span=
 id=3D"S4.SS2.SSS1.Px2.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">MR1</span> =
serves as a meaningful indicator of behavioral fidelity.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S4.SS2.SSS1.Px3" class=3D"ltx_paragraph">
<h5 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_font_bold ltx_title_paragraph">Evaluation metric=
</h5>

<div id=3D"S4.SS2.SSS1.Px3.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS2.SSS1.Px3.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">To measure this MR, we consi=
der the <span id=3D"S4.SS2.SSS1.Px3.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_ital=
ic">Label Loyalty</span> metric that quantifies the degree to which this MR=
 holds across all the test instances. It computes the percentage of instanc=
es for which the student model=E2=80=99s prediction matches the teacher mod=
el=E2=80=99s prediction, analogous to accuracy:</p>
</div>
