<section id=3D"S4.SS2.SSS4.Px2" class=3D"ltx_paragraph">
<h5 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_font_bold ltx_title_paragraph">Rationale</h5>

<div id=3D"S4.SS2.SSS4.Px2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS2.SSS4.Px2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Top-1 agreement alone does n=
ot indicate whether the student model is <em id=3D"S4.SS2.SSS4.Px2.p1.1.1" =
class=3D"ltx_emph ltx_font_italic">well-calibrated</em>. Poor calibration, =
where predicted probabilities do not reflect true likelihoods, can lead to =
over- or under-confidence, which adversely affects downstream decision-maki=
ng. Prior studies <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Shang<span cl=
ass=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/=
html/2511.05476#bib.bib120" title=3D"Enhancing post-training quantization c=
alibration through contrastive learning" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024</a>], Ji<sp=
an class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv=
.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib121" title=3D"Beware of calibration data for pr=
uning large language models" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024</a>]</cite> on vision a=
nd language models demonstrate that compression techniques such as quantiza=
tion can significantly distort model calibration, even when accuracy remain=
s unaffected. These findings motivate the design of this MR to assess behav=
ioral fidelity through the lens of calibration alignment. To ensure that ou=
r analysis is not sensitive to a specific binning configuration, we evaluat=
e calibration alignment across multiple values of <math id=3D"S4.SS2.SSS4.P=
x2.p1.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"B" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":=
literal"><semantics><mi>B</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">B<=
/annotation></semantics></math> to observe consistent trends in the relativ=
e behavior of teacher and student models.</p>
</div>
</section>
