<section id=3D"S4.SS3" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">4.3 </span><span id=3D"S4.SS3.1.=
1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> Evaluation</h3>

<div id=3D"S4.SS3.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS3.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">To evaluate the effectiveness of the =
proposed <span id=3D"S4.SS3.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Meta=
Compress</span> framework, we perform an extensive empirical study using th=
e models, datasets, and knowledge distillation techniques described in Sect=
ion <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S3.SS1" title=3D"3.1 Study=
 Design =E2=80=A3 3 Empirical Study =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Testing Perspec=
tive on Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code: Does the Studen=
t Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_=
ref_tag">3.1</span></a>. This evaluation aims to determine whether <span id=
=3D"S4.SS3.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> c=
an uncover behavioral discrepancies between teacher and student models that=
 traditional accuracy-based metrics fail to capture.</p>
</div>
<section id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS1" class=3D"ltx_subsubsection">
<h4 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsubsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsubsection">4.3.1 </span>Implementations<=
/h4>

<div id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS1.p1.1.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> is implemented in Py=
thon on top of the <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS1.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_fo=
nt_italic">Compressor</span>, <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS1.p1.1.3" class=3D"ltx_=
text ltx_font_italic" style=3D"font-size:120%;">A<span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS1.p1=
.1.3.1" class=3D"ltx_text" style=3D"font-size:83%;">VATAR</span></span>, an=
d <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS1.p1.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH<=
/span>. All experiments are conducted on an Ubuntu 22.04 machine equipped w=
ith an Intel(R) Xeon(R) W-2265 CPU @ 3.50GHz, 256 GB RAM, and one NVIDIA RT=
X A6000 48 GB GPU.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2" class=3D"ltx_subsubsection">
<h4 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsubsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsubsection">4.3.2 </span>Evaluation Resul=
ts</h4>

<div id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">This section presents the empiri=
cal evaluation results of the <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_=
text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> framework to address the second r=
esearch question, <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_fon=
t_bold">RQ2</span>: <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p1.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_f=
ont_italic">To what extent does MetaCompress uncover behavioral discrepanci=
es that may not be captured by the traditional accuracy metric?</span></p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">We address this research questio=
n by assessing the effectiveness of the <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p2.1.1" cla=
ss=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> framework by measuring =
the degree of violation across the four designed metamorphic relations. Eac=
h violation indicates a behavioral inconsistency between the teacher and st=
udent models when exposed to identical inputs, thus quantifying the loss of=
 behavioral fidelity after knowledge distillation. We conduct this analysis=
 across two language models of code (CodeBERT and GraphCodeBERT), two softw=
are analytics tasks (clone detection and vulnerability prediction), and thr=
ee knowledge distillation approaches (<span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p2.1.2" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span>, <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p2=
.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span>, and <span id=3D"S4.=
SS3.SSS2.p2.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span>).</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p3.1" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p3.1.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">MR1 violation:</span> The results for <spa=
n id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p3.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">MR1</span> vio=
lation shown in Figure <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S4.F6" =
title=3D"Figure 6 =E2=80=A3 4.3.2 Evaluation Results =E2=80=A3 4.3 MetaComp=
ress Evaluation =E2=80=A3 4 Approach: MetaCompress Framework =E2=80=A3 A Me=
tamorphic Testing Perspective on Knowledge Distillation for Language Models=
 of Code: Does the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><sp=
an class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">6</span></a> reveal that student models e=
xhibit low violation rates for the clone detection task but considerably hi=
gher rates for vulnerability prediction. For clone detection, all three dis=
tillation techniques maintain strong label agreement with the teacher, with=
 a maximum violation of 7%, where <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p3.1.3" class=3D"=
ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span> achieves the lowest (3%) and <span i=
d=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p3.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span> t=
he highest (7%) inconsistency. In contrast, violation rates rise sharply fo=
r vulnerability prediction, ranging from 29% to 36%, indicating notable beh=
avioral divergence between teacher and student models. Among the methods, <=
span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p3.1.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</s=
pan> performs slightly better for <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p3.1.6" class=3D"=
ltx_text ltx_font_italic">CodeBERT</span>, while <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p3=
.1.7" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span> and <span id=3D"S4.SS=
3.SSS2.p3.1.8" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span> show co=
mparable fidelity across both models. As shown in Table <a href=3D"https://=
arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S3.T1" title=3D"Table 1 =E2=80=A3 3.2 Empirical R=
esults =E2=80=A3 3 Empirical Study =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Testing Perspect=
ive on Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code: Does the Student=
 Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_r=
ef_tag">1</span></a>, although the student models achieve comparable perfor=
mance on the vulnerability prediction task (with a maximum accuracy differe=
nce of approximately 3%), the <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p3.1.9" class=3D"ltx_=
text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> framework reveals up to 36% discr=
epancies in prediction alignment, demonstrating its ability to capture beha=
vioral differences that traditional accuracy-based evaluation overlooks.</p=
>
</div>
