 title=3D"Figure 7 =E2=80=A3 4.3.2 Evaluation Results =E2=80=A3 4.3 MetaCom=
press Evaluation =E2=80=A3 4 Approach: MetaCompress Framework =E2=80=A3 A M=
etamorphic Testing Perspective on Knowledge Distillation for Language Model=
s of Code: Does the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><s=
pan class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">7</span></a> reveal that the degree of p=
robabilistic divergence between teacher and student models varies across ta=
sks and distillation techniques. For the clone detection task, the violatio=
n rates remain relatively low, ranging from 3% to 13%, suggesting that the =
student models generally approximate the teacher=E2=80=99s output distribut=
ions. In contrast, the vulnerability prediction task shows substantially gr=
eater violations, reaching up to 31%, reflecting a pronounced mismatch in t=
he probability distributions of the teacher and student models. These findi=
ngs suggest that, although the student models can match the teacher=E2=80=
=99s predictions in terms of label accuracy, their underlying probability d=
istributions differ significantly, underscoring <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p4.=
1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> =E2=80=99s abil=
ity to expose fine-grained probabilistic discrepancies beyond traditional a=
ccuracy-based evaluation.</p>
</div>
