<div id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p6" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p6.2" class=3D"ltx_p"><span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p6.2.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">MR3 violation:</span> While MR1 and MR2 ex=
pose surface-level inconsistencies, such as label disagreement and output d=
istribution shifts, MR3 uncovers deeper deviations in behavioral fidelity. =
Table <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S4.T2" title=3D"Table 2 =
=E2=80=A3 4.3.2 Evaluation Results =E2=80=A3 4.3 MetaCompress Evaluation =
=E2=80=A3 4 Approach: MetaCompress Framework =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Testin=
g Perspective on Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code: Does t=
he Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_=
text ltx_ref_tag">2</span></a> illustrates the violations of MR3 observed i=
n student models, as identified by the <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p6.2.2" clas=
s=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span>. Across all tasks and st=
udent models, we observe substantial violations of MR3. As shown in Table <=
a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S4.T2" title=3D"Table 2 =E2=80=
=A3 4.3.2 Evaluation Results =E2=80=A3 4.3 MetaCompress Evaluation =E2=80=
=A3 4 Approach: MetaCompress Framework =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Testing Pers=
pective on Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code: Does the Stu=
dent Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text l=
tx_ref_tag">2</span></a>, student GraphCodeBERT models often exhibit signif=
icantly lower confidence than their teacher counterparts for the vulnerabil=
ity prediction task, despite having similar accuracy. For example, the Grap=
hCodeBERT model obtained from <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p6.2.3" class=3D"ltx_=
text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span> violates up to <span id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.=
p6.2.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_bold">62%</span> of MR3, indicating a si=
gnificant discrepancy in high-confidence predictions and overall behavioral=
 fidelity between the teacher and student models that accuracy-based evalua=
tion fails to capture. We further examine the sensitivity of MR3 to differe=
nt threshold values of <math id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p6.1.m1" class=3D"ltx_Math" =
alttext=3D"\tau" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><semantics><mi>=CF=
=84</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\tau</annotation></seman=
tics></math> and find that variations in <math id=3D"S4.SS3.SSS2.p6.2.m2" c=
lass=3D"ltx_Math" alttext=3D"\tau" display=3D"inline" intent=3D":literal"><=
semantics><mi>=CF=84</mi><annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">\tau</a=
nnotation></semantics></math> had a negligible impact on overall violation =
rates, confirming the metric=E2=80=99s stability.</p>
</div>
