<section id=3D"Sx1" class=3D"ltx_section">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">Robustness Analysis of <span id=
=3D"Sx1.2.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span>
</h2>

<div id=3D"Sx1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"Sx1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">To assess the robustness of <span id=3D"=
Sx1.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> as an ev=
aluation framework, we conduct an ablation study to determine whether its c=
onclusions remain consistent when the inputs to both the teacher and studen=
t models are transformed for the vulnerability prediction task. Specificall=
y, we recompute MR1=E2=80=93MR4 violations using transformed inputs and com=
pare the resulting behavioral fidelity patterns with those obtained from th=
e original inputs. To obtain transformed inputs, we use metamorphic code<sp=
an id=3D"footnote8" class=3D"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote"><sup class=3D"ltx_=
note_mark">8</sup><span class=3D"ltx_note_outer"><span class=3D"ltx_note_co=
ntent"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">8</sup><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_n=
ote">8</span>Unlike adversarial examples, which are generated through itera=
tive identifier modifications guided by queries to the target model, metamo=
rphic code is obtained through a one-time transformation of identifier name=
s that preserves program semantics.</span></span></span> generated followin=
g Panichella et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Panichella =
[<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib29" title=3D"Metamorph=
ic-based many-objective distillation of llms for code-related tasks" class=
=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>]</cite>, which applies semantics-preserving transform=
ations such as method and parameter renaming. Identifiers are replaced with=
 meaningful synonyms (e.g., <span id=3D"Sx1.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_f=
ont_italic">args</span> to <span id=3D"Sx1.p1.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_fo=
nt_italic">arguments</span>) using <span id=3D"Sx1.p1.1.4" class=3D"ltx_tex=
t ltx_font_italic">ChatGPT-3.5</span> to ensure naturalness. The generated =
code is validated for syntactic correctness using <span id=3D"Sx1.p1.1.5" c=
lass=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">tree-sitter</span>, with a subset manuall=
y inspected for semantic equivalence.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"Sx1.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"Sx1.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">The results presented in Table&nbsp;<a h=
ref=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#Sx1.T4" title=3D"Table 4 =E2=80=A3=
 Robustness Analysis of MetaCompress =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Testing Perspe=
ctive on Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code: Does the Stude=
nt Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx=
_ref_tag">4</span></a> indicate that the predictive performance of compress=
ed models is comparable to that of uncompressed models when evaluated on me=
tamorphically transformed inputs. The differences in accuracy between the u=
ncompressed and compressed models generated by <span id=3D"Sx1.p2.1.1" clas=
s=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span>, <span id=3D"Sx1.p2.1.2" c=
lass=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span>, and <span id=3D"Sx1.p2.1.3=
" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span> are minimal for both Code=
BERT and GraphCodeBERT. These findings indicate that, according to conventi=
onal accuracy-based evaluation, compressed models maintain task-level perfo=
rmance following input transformations.</p>
</div>
