<section id=3D"S5" class=3D"ltx_section">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section">5 </span>Discussion</h2>

<section id=3D"S5.SS1" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">5.1 </span>Behavioral Fidelity a=
nd Knowledge Gap in Knowledge Distillation</h3>

<div id=3D"S5.SS1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.SS1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Ba et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx=
_citemacro_cite">Ba and Caruana [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.054=
76#bib.bib117" title=3D"Do deep nets really need to be deep?" class=3D"ltx_=
ref">2014</a>]</cite> stated that =E2=80=9D<span id=3D"S5.SS1.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">If the student model learns to mimic the teac=
her model perfectly, it makes exactly the same predictions and mistakes as =
the teacher model.</span>=E2=80=9D However, achieving such mimicry is extre=
mely challenging when there exists a substantial gap in network capacity <c=
ite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Wang and Yoon [<a href=3D"https:/=
/arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib116" title=3D"Knowledge distillation and =
student-teacher learning for visual intelligence: a review and new outlooks=
" class=3D"ltx_ref">2021</a>]</cite>. For instance, the knowledge distillat=
ion technique <span id=3D"S5.SS1.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic"=
>Compressor</span> reduces the size of the <span id=3D"S5.SS1.p1.1.3" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">CodeBERT</span> model from 476 MB to only 3 M=
B. Consequently, although the student models produced by <span id=3D"S5.SS1=
.p1.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span>, <span id=3D"=
S5.SS1.p1.1.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span>, and <span =
id=3D"S5.SS1.p1.1.6" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span> achiev=
e accuracy comparable to the teacher, their performance deteriorates consid=
erably under adversarial attacks. Even though <span id=3D"S5.SS1.p1.1.7" cl=
ass=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span> attempts to distill knowledge=
 more robustly by incorporating metamorphic attacks through metamorphic cod=
e transformations, the resulting student models still exhibit notable adver=
sarial vulnerabilities. These observations indicate that the knowledge dist=
illation strategies employed by <span id=3D"S5.SS1.p1.1.8" class=3D"ltx_tex=
t ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span>, <span id=3D"S5.SS1.p1.1.9" class=3D"l=
tx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span>, and <span id=3D"S5.SS1.p1.1.10" cla=
ss=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span> do not enable the student mode=
ls to deeply mimic the teacher=E2=80=99s behavior, leaving a substantial <s=
pan id=3D"S5.SS1.p1.1.11" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">knowledge gap<=
/span> in behavioral fidelity between the teacher and the student models.</=
p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S5.SS1.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.SS1.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">One might argue that a student model =
performs comparably to its teacher after knowledge distillation. Then, <spa=
n id=3D"S5.SS1.p2.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">why should we be =
concerned about the knowledge gap in behavioral fidelity</span>? We address=
 this question through two key arguments.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"S5.SS1.p3" class=3D"ltx_para">
<ol id=3D"S5.I1" class=3D"ltx_enumerate">
<li id=3D"S5.I1.i1" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">1.</span>=20
<div id=3D"S5.I1.i1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.I1.i1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">If the knowledge gap can be reduced=
 by enabling the student model to more deeply mimic the teacher model, then=
 the student should exhibit comparable robustness to its teacher under adve=
rsarial conditions. This would make the student model suitable for deployme=
nt in real-world software systems where safety and reliability are critical=
.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S5.I1.i2" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">2.</span>=20
<div id=3D"S5.I1.i2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.I1.i2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Wang et al. <cite class=3D"ltx_cite=
 ltx_citemacro_cite">Wang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</spa=
n> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib30" title=3D"An emp=
irical study of knowledge distillation for code understanding tasks" class=
=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>]</cite> empirically demonstrated that the same studen=
t model distilled from a teacher performs significantly better than when tr=
ained using the standard fine-tuning approach on the same task. Since the t=
eacher model typically possesses much greater network capacity, it can lear=
n more complex decision boundaries and have greater robustness against adve=
rsarial attacks. Minimizing the <span id=3D"S5.I1.i2.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_t=
ext ltx_font_italic">knowledge gap</span>, therefore, enables the distilled=
 student model to better approximate these boundaries during distillation, =
potentially enhancing its resilience to adversarial attacks.</p>
</div>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div id=3D"S5.SS1.p4" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.SS1.p4.1" class=3D"ltx_p">The empirical findings from our <span=
 id=3D"S5.SS1.p4.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span=
> framework substantiate these arguments. Although the accuracy difference =
between teacher and student models remains within 3%, <span id=3D"S5.SS1.p4=
.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> reveals violat=
ions of up to 62% across the four metamorphic relations, indicating substan=
tial discrepancies in behavioral fidelity. For instance, the high MR1 and M=
R2 violation rates demonstrate that the student models often diverge from t=
he teacher in both label agreement and probability distribution, even when =
their predictions appear similar at the aggregate level. Likewise, MR3 and =
MR4 violations expose inconsistencies in confidence and calibration alignme=
nt, underscoring that accuracy alone cannot fully capture behavioral diverg=
ence. These results confirm that reducing the <span id=3D"S5.SS1.p4.1.3" cl=
ass=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">knowledge gap</span> in behavioral fidelit=
y is essential for developing distilled models that preserve the robustness=
 and decision consistency of their teacher counterparts. These insights ope=
n promising avenues for advancing knowledge distillation methods that achie=
ve greater alignment between student and teacher models in terms of predict=
ive behavior, internal representations, generalizability, and robustness.</=
p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S5.SS2" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">5.2 </span>Practical Considerati=
on and Deployment Cost</h3>

<div id=3D"S5.SS2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.SS2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">From a practical standpoint, evaluati=
ng the behavioral fidelity does not impose significant overhead. <span id=
=3D"S5.SS2.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> i=
s designed exclusively as an evaluation framework to determine whether a di=
stilled student model deeply mimics its teacher prior to deployment. In sta=
ndard knowledge distillation workflows, both the teacher and student models=
 are evaluated on held-out test data to assess predictive performance, whic=
h requires forward passes through both models. <span id=3D"S5.SS2.p1.1.2" c=
lass=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> leverages the probabi=
lity distributions and related outputs generated during this routine evalua=
tion as byproducts, without requiring additional model executions. Therefor=
e, even for teams that frequently conduct model distillation, <span id=3D"S=
5.SS2.p1.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> introd=
uces only negligible computational overhead beyond lightweight post-process=
ing. This approach is both practical and scalable for diagnosing behavioral=
 fidelity gaps and ensuring that compressed student models are robust and r=
eliable for real-world deployment.</p>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S5.SS3" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">5.3 </span>Actionable Insights f=
or Practitioners and Researchers</h3>

<div id=3D"S5.SS3.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.SS3.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Although <span id=3D"S5.SS3.p1.1.1" c=
lass=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> reports violation rat=
es as diagnostic measures of behavioral fidelity divergence, these values s=
hould not be interpreted in isolation. Instead, they serve as actionable in=
dicators, grounded in the empirical observations of this study, such as sub=
stantial robustness gaps and MR violations. These indicators inform decisio=
n-making throughout the model development and deployment pipeline.</p>
</div>
<section id=3D"S5.SS3.SSS1" class=3D"ltx_subsubsection">
<h4 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsubsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsubsection">5.3.1 </span>Insights for Pra=
ctitioners</h4>

<div id=3D"S5.SS3.SSS1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<ol id=3D"S5.I2" class=3D"ltx_enumerate">
<li id=3D"S5.I2.i1" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">1.</span>=20
<div id=3D"S5.I2.i1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.I2.i1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">The appropriate response to an obse=
rved metamorphic relation (MR) violation rate depends on the intended deplo=
yment context and the acceptable level of risk. For example, a student mode=
l with a low violation rate (e.g., below 10%) may be considered sufficientl=
y stable for use in non-critical applications, such as software clone detec=
tion. In contrast, for security-critical tasks (e.g., vulnerability detecti=
on) or adversarially exposed environments, practitioners should exercise gr=
eater caution and avoid deploying highly compact models. Therefore, it is r=
ecommended that practitioners integrate violation-rate checks into continuo=
us integration and deployment pipelines to serve as a gating criterion for =
model release. Models exhibiting low violation rates may be suitable for de=
ployment in non-critical applications. In contrast, models designed for sec=
urity-sensitive or adversarial environments should adhere to more stringent=
 thresholds or be supplemented with additional safeguards, such as adversar=
ial defenses or post-deployment monitoring, prior to release.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S5.I2.i2" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">2.</span>=20
<div id=3D"S5.I2.i2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.I2.i2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">The acceptable metamorphic relation=
 (MR) violation rate also depends on both the model and the application con=
text. For instance, Figure <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S4.=
F6" title=3D"Figure 6 =E2=80=A3 4.3.2 Evaluation Results =E2=80=A3 4.3 Meta=
Compress Evaluation =E2=80=A3 4 Approach: MetaCompress Framework =E2=80=A3 =
A Metamorphic Testing Perspective on Knowledge Distillation for Language Mo=
dels of Code: Does the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"=
><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">6</span></a> demonstrates that studen=
t models exhibit low MR1 violation rates (up to 7%) for the clone detection=
 task, but substantially higher rates (up to 36%) for vulnerability predict=
ion. A similar pattern is observed for MR2 violations (Figure <a href=3D"ht=
tps://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#footnote7" title=3D"footnote 7 =E2=80=A3 Fi=
gure 8 =E2=80=A3 4.3.2 Evaluation Results =E2=80=A3 4.3 MetaCompress Evalua=
tion =E2=80=A3 4 Approach: MetaCompress Framework =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic T=
esting Perspective on Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code: D=
oes the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D=
"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">7</span></a>), reaching up to 31% in the vulnerabili=
ty prediction task. As presented in Table <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html=
/2511.05476#S4.T2" title=3D"Table 2 =E2=80=A3 4.3.2 Evaluation Results =E2=
=80=A3 4.3 MetaCompress Evaluation =E2=80=A3 4 Approach: MetaCompress Frame=
work =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Testing Perspective on Knowledge Distillation =
for Language Models of Code: Does the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" cl=
ass=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">2</span></a>, compress=
ed GraphCodeBERT models derived from AVATAR violate up to 62% of MR3 in the=
 vulnerability prediction task. In contrast, the highest MR4 violation (up =
to 0.142 as shown in Table <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S4.=
T3" title=3D"Table 3 =E2=80=A3 4.3.2 Evaluation Results =E2=80=A3 4.3 MetaC=
ompress Evaluation =E2=80=A3 4 Approach: MetaCompress Framework =E2=80=A3 A=
 Metamorphic Testing Perspective on Knowledge Distillation for Language Mod=
els of Code: Does the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref">=
<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">3</span></a>) occurs in the clone dete=
ction task. These findings indicate that practitioners should interpret MR =
violation rates in the context of both the specific task and the model conf=
iguration, and make deployment decisions by weighing behavioral divergence =
against the application=E2=80=99s risk tolerance.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S5.I2.i3" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">3.</span>=20
<div id=3D"S5.I2.i3.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.I2.i3.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">The metamorphic relation violation =
rates indicate substantial behavioral divergence between teacher and studen=
t models within a specific application context, as shown in Figures <a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S4.F6" title=3D"Figure 6 =E2=80=A3 4.=
3.2 Evaluation Results =E2=80=A3 4.3 MetaCompress Evaluation =E2=80=A3 4 Ap=
proach: MetaCompress Framework =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Testing Perspective =
on Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code: Does the Student Dee=
ply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_t=
ag">6</span></a>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#footnote7" t=
itle=3D"footnote 7 =E2=80=A3 Figure 8 =E2=80=A3 4.3.2 Evaluation Results =
=E2=80=A3 4.3 MetaCompress Evaluation =E2=80=A3 4 Approach: MetaCompress Fr=
amework =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Testing Perspective on Knowledge Distillati=
on for Language Models of Code: Does the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?"=
 class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">7</span></a>, and T=
ables <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S4.T2" title=3D"Table 2 =
=E2=80=A3 4.3.2 Evaluation Results =E2=80=A3 4.3 MetaCompress Evaluation =
=E2=80=A3 4 Approach: MetaCompress Framework =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Testin=
g Perspective on Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code: Does t=
he Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_=
text ltx_ref_tag">2</span></a>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.0547=
6#S4.T3" title=3D"Table 3 =E2=80=A3 4.3.2 Evaluation Results =E2=80=A3 4.3 =
MetaCompress Evaluation =E2=80=A3 4 Approach: MetaCompress Framework =E2=80=
=A3 A Metamorphic Testing Perspective on Knowledge Distillation for Languag=
e Models of Code: Does the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_=
ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">3</span></a>. Therefore, practiti=
oners should consider revisiting the selected student architecture or adopt=
ing a knowledge distillation strategy informed by the MR violations. For in=
stance, in the clone detection task, the CodeBERT and GraphCodeBERT models =
derived from <span id=3D"S5.I2.i3.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic=
">AVATAR</span> exhibit higher MR1 violation rates (7%) than those from <sp=
an id=3D"S5.I2.i3.p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</sp=
an> (3%) and <span id=3D"S5.I2.i3.p1.1.3" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic=
">MORPH</span> (5%). A similar trend is observed for MR2 violations: models=
 obtained via the <span id=3D"S5.I2.i3.p1.1.4" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_i=
talic">AVATAR</span> knowledge distillation approach exhibit higher MR viol=
ations (13% for CodeBERT and 19% for GraphCodeBERT) than those from <span i=
d=3D"S5.I2.i3.p1.1.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span> =
and <span id=3D"S5.I2.i3.p1.1.6" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</=
span>. Conversely, in the vulnerability detection task, models produced by =
<span id=3D"S5.I2.i3.p1.1.7" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</spa=
n> demonstrate lower MR3 violations than those generated by <span id=3D"S5.=
I2.i3.p1.1.8" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor</span> and <spa=
n id=3D"S5.I2.i3.p1.1.9" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span>. T=
hese findings indicate that <span id=3D"S5.I2.i3.p1.1.10" class=3D"ltx_text=
 ltx_font_italic">MetaCompress</span> can assist practitioners in selecting=
 suitable compression techniques for specific models and tasks, thereby ens=
uring that knowledge-distilled models more accurately mimic the learned rep=
resentations and decision boundaries of their teacher models.</p>
</div>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
</section>
<section id=3D"S5.SS3.SSS2" class=3D"ltx_subsubsection">
<h4 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsubsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsubsection">5.3.2 </span>Insights for Res=
earchers</h4>

<div id=3D"S5.SS3.SSS2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<ol id=3D"S5.I3" class=3D"ltx_enumerate">
<li id=3D"S5.I3.i1" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">1.</span>=20
<div id=3D"S5.I3.i1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.I3.i1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">From a research perspective, MR vio=
lation rates offer a quantitative measure for assessing knowledge transfer =
quality that extends beyond traditional accuracy metrics. As shown in our e=
xperimental results, student models often achieve comparable accuracy to te=
acher models while exhibiting significant MR violations and reduced adversa=
rial robustness, indicating incomplete transfer of decision boundaries. For=
 example, in Figure&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S4.F5=
" title=3D"Figure 5 =E2=80=A3 4.2 Designing Output-Based Metamorphic Relati=
ons =E2=80=A3 4 Approach: MetaCompress Framework =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Te=
sting Perspective on Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code: Do=
es the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"=
ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">5</span></a>, the teacher assigns a confidence score =
of 0.99, while the student assigns 0.51 for the same instance (e.g., idx: 2=
1383), and this discrepancy is captured by MR2. These observations suggest =
that relying solely on soft targets for knowledge distillation may not adeq=
uately transfer the teacher=E2=80=99s decision boundaries and internal repr=
esentations. These observations suggest that reducing MR violations require=
s improving the transfer of knowledge quality from the teacher to the stude=
nt beyond final predictions. To this end, researchers may incorporate inter=
mediate-layer alignment, such as matching hidden representations or attenti=
on distributions <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Jiao<span clas=
s=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/ht=
ml/2511.05476#bib.bib67" title=3D"Tinybert: distilling bert for natural lan=
guage understanding" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>], Wang<span class=3D"ltx_te=
xt ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.054=
76#bib.bib68" title=3D"Minilm: deep self-attention distillation for task-ag=
nostic compression of pre-trained transformers" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020b</a>=
, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib69" title=3D"Minilmv2=
: multi-head self-attention relation distillation for compressing pretraine=
d transformers" class=3D"ltx_ref">2021a</a>], Sun<span class=3D"ltx_text lt=
x_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bi=
b.bib70" title=3D"Mobilebert: a compact task-agnostic bert for resource-lim=
ited devices" class=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>]</cite>, designing distribution-le=
vel alignment losses <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Park<span =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.or=
g/html/2511.05476#bib.bib71" title=3D"Relational knowledge distillation" cl=
ass=3D"ltx_ref">2019</a>]</cite>, and applying robustness-aware distillatio=
n objectives <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Goldblum<span clas=
s=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/ht=
ml/2511.05476#bib.bib72" title=3D"Adversarially robust distillation" class=
=3D"ltx_ref">2020</a>], Zi<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</sp=
an> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib73" title=3D"Revis=
iting adversarial robustness distillation: robust soft labels make student =
better" class=3D"ltx_ref">2021</a>]</cite> that better preserve the teacher=
 model=E2=80=99s confidence and calibration behavior.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S5.I3.i2" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">2.</span>=20
<div id=3D"S5.I3.i2.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.I3.i2.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Our empirical findings indicate tha=
t robustness degradation persists across compressed models trained with var=
ious knowledge distillation techniques (e.g., <span id=3D"S5.I3.i2.p1.1.1" =
class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">AVATAR</span> and <span id=3D"S5.I3.i2.p=
1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">MORPH</span> in Figures <a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#S3.F2" title=3D"Figure 2 =E2=80=A3 3.=
2 Empirical Results =E2=80=A3 3 Empirical Study =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Tes=
ting Perspective on Knowledge Distillation for Language Models of Code: Doe=
s the Student Deeply Mimic the Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"l=
tx_text ltx_ref_tag">2</span></a> and <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/251=
1.05476#S3.F3" title=3D"Figure 3 =E2=80=A3 3.2 Empirical Results =E2=80=A3 =
3 Empirical Study =E2=80=A3 A Metamorphic Testing Perspective on Knowledge =
Distillation for Language Models of Code: Does the Student Deeply Mimic the=
 Teacher?" class=3D"ltx_ref"><span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_ref_tag">3</span><=
/a>). This persistence suggests that a single-teacher distillation process =
may not adequately capture the diverse decision regions within the input sp=
ace. This limitation aligns with the findings of Yang et al. <cite class=3D=
"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Yang<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et=
 al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib64" title=
=3D"One-for-all does not work! enhancing vulnerability detection by mixture=
-of-experts (moe)" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025b</a>]</cite>, who demonstrated th=
at Mixture of Experts (MoE) <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Jac=
obs<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https:/=
/arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib92" title=3D"Adaptive mixtures of local e=
xperts" class=3D"ltx_ref">1991</a>]</cite> frameworks improve software vuln=
erability detection compared to single-model approaches. Based on these ins=
ights, future research should investigate multi-teacher knowledge distillat=
ion leveraging MoE architectures to aggregate complementary knowledge from =
multiple specialized teachers <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">A=
wal<span class=3D"ltx_text ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https:/=
/arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib88" title=3D"MoEKD: mixture-of-experts kn=
owledge distillation for robust and high-performing compressed code models"=
 class=3D"ltx_ref">2026</a>]</cite>.</p>
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"S5.I3.i3" class=3D"ltx_item" style=3D"list-style-type:none;">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">3.</span>=20
<div id=3D"S5.I3.i3.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.I3.i3.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">Finally, the experimental results i=
ndicate that current knowledge distillation approaches primarily focus on a=
ligning final-layer outputs, yet significant behavioral discrepancies persi=
st, as evidenced by high MR violation rates and adversarial vulnerability g=
aps. These findings imply that essential structural and representational in=
formation is lost during the distillation process, and that soft knowledge =
alignment alone does not adequately preserve behavioral fidelity. Future re=
search should explore hybrid distillation strategies that integrate output-=
level supervision with intermediate-layer alignment and behavioral constrai=
nts designed in our <span id=3D"S5.I3.i3.p1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font=
_italic">MetaCompress</span> framework, aiming to minimize MR violations an=
d enhance behavioral fidelity between teacher and student models.</p>
</div>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div id=3D"S5.SS3.SSS2.p2" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S5.SS3.SSS2.p2.1" class=3D"ltx_p">In summary, the insights above s=
uggest that behavioral fidelity divergence and metamorphic relation violati=
on rates should be interpreted as decision-support metrics rather than pass=
=E2=80=93fail criteria. By making decision-boundary instability observable =
and measurable, <span id=3D"S5.SS3.SSS2.p2.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_=
italic">MetaCompress</span> enables developers to make informed follow-up d=
ecisions=E2=80=94such as pursuing architectural refinements or accepting a =
model based on application-specific risk tolerance=E2=80=94and encourages r=
esearchers in designing more robust and reliable knowledge distillation tec=
hniques.</p>
</div>
</section>
</section>
</section>
<section id=3D"S6" class=3D"ltx_section">
<h2 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_section">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_section">6 </span>Threats to Validity</h2>

<div id=3D"S6.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S6.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">This section provides a brief overview of=
 the construct and the internal and external threats associated with our st=
udy.</p>
</div>
<section id=3D"S6.SS1" class=3D"ltx_subsection">
<h3 class=3D"ltx_title ltx_title_subsection">
<span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_subsection">6.1 </span>Internal Validity</h3=
>

<div id=3D"S6.SS1.p1" class=3D"ltx_para">
<p id=3D"S6.SS1.p1.1" class=3D"ltx_p">A potential threat to internal validi=
ty may arise if differences in performance between the student and teacher =
models are influenced by inconsistent training procedures, fine-tuning conf=
igurations, or data handling, rather than the knowledge distillation approa=
ches themselves. To mitigate this threat, we applied uniform training proto=
cols and hyperparameter settings across all models, both student and teache=
r, following the configurations reported in prior knowledge distillation st=
udies <cite class=3D"ltx_cite ltx_citemacro_cite">Shi<span class=3D"ltx_tex=
t ltx_bib_etal"> et al.</span> [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.0547=
6#bib.bib6" title=3D"Compressing pre-trained models of code into 3 mb" clas=
s=3D"ltx_ref">2023</a>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bi=
b8" title=3D"Greening large language models of code" class=3D"ltx_ref">2024=
a</a>], Panichella [<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/html/2511.05476#bib.bib29"=
 title=3D"Metamorphic-based many-objective distillation of llms for code-re=
lated tasks" class=3D"ltx_ref">2025</a>]</cite>. Additionally, we used iden=
tical data splits for fine-tuning and evaluation to ensure consistency and =
fairness in comparison. Maintaining such a consistent experimental setup en=
hances the internal validity of our findings by ensuring that the observed =
effects are due to the student model=E2=80=99s inability to deeply mimic th=
e teacher model=E2=80=99s behavior, rather than differences in hyperparamet=
ers or data partitions. Additionally, the experimental results may be influ=
enced by potential errors in implementing the training pipelines for both s=
tudent and teacher models. To mitigate this threat, we adopted the standard=
ized training procedures provided by the <span id=3D"S6.SS1.p1.1.1" class=
=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">CodeXGLUE</span> benchmark for teacher model =
fine-tuning and evaluation. For knowledge distillation, we utilized publicl=
y available, off-the-shelf student models obtained from <span id=3D"S6.SS1.=
p1.1.2" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Compressor<span id=3D"footnote9"=
 class=3D"ltx_note ltx_role_footnote"><sup class=3D"ltx_note_mark">9</sup><=
span class=3D"ltx_note_outer"><span class=3D"ltx_note_content"><sup class=
=3D"ltx_note_mark">9</sup><span class=3D"ltx_tag ltx_tag_note"><span id=3D"=
footnote9.1.1.1" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_upright">9</span></span><span i=
d=3D"footnote9.5" class=3D"ltx_text ltx_font_upright">https://github.com/so=
arsmu/Compressor</span></span></span></span></span>, <span id=3D"S6.SS1.p1.=
